Managing a business as a creative introvert who values their private life should not be complicated, and yet it sometimes is. Most online resources and coaches tell you to work with big (and diabolical) tech companies using extrovert techniques. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, share who you are. Have your service reviewed, be available 24/7, respond to questions with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
01/03/2024
This is a year of transition for me.
I don't want to fuel the big tech companies with my money, data, and energy. Nor do I want coaches who have only one extrovert solution that they apply to everyone. I'm exploring new ways to manage my activity while fighting against the idea that I've long believed in, that you have to do things a certain way to succeed.
Wish me luck!
I've already taken the first steps.
I've left FB, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
I've also removed the last external tracker, Google Analytics, from my website yesterday and it feels good.
I recently subscribed to a European-based CRM for better GDPR compliance, and I'll be transferring my activity over the next few weeks.
I've transferred my MX to Proton and I'm now fully benefiting from SPF, DKIM, and DMARC without having to pay Google for basic email address validation.
03/03/2024
